  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as if it came from a legitimate source.\n\n**Key Points:**\n1. **Legal Framework:** Most countries have laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering. These laws are often part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks.\n  \n2. **International Cooperation:** Money laundering is considered a serious crime globally, and there are international agreements and organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), that work to combat it.\n\n3. **Penalties:** The penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, confiscation of assets, and lengthy prison sentences. Both individuals and organizations can be held accountable.\n\n4. **Obligations for Businesses:** Financial institutions and certain other businesses are required to have AML programs in place to detect and report suspicious activities. This includes customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting large or suspicious transactions to authorities.\n\n5. **Types of Activities:** Money laundering can involve various activities, including but not limited to, structuring transactions to avoid reporting thresholds, using shell companies, and engaging in trade-based money laundering.\n\nGiven the serious implications and the global commitment to combating it, money laundering is strictly prohibited and actively prosecuted.",
